      <h2>The Story</h2>
      <p><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0211/0380/t/4/assets/stephen-Jones-loadmaster-c17-4.jpg"></p>
      <p>Back in 2012, while I was a flyer for the United States Air Force, I had a desire to start something that would have great meaning for myself. I was stationed in Germany for a short period of time, and during that time I was flying missions all over the Middle East. Kuwait, Qatar, Pakistan, Afghanistan, and everything that surrounded those countries.</p>
      <p>We were tasked for a special mission to fly Leon Panetta, the Secretary of Defense at the time, from Kuwait to an undisclosed location, and then to Afghanistan to meet with some higher ups. We weren’t given all of the details, but we knew it was important.</p>
      <p>When we escorted high ranking individuals we often flew with the “Silver Bullet”. A metal capsule that fit into our jet that was the exoskeleton of a mini suite. Leather sofas, armchairs, oak tables, a bed, restroom, and LED TV’s for the DV (distinguished visitor) to hold conference calls while in flight.</p>
      <p><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0211/0380/t/4/assets/c17-globemaster.jpg"></p>
      <p>We were equipped with a Raven and Viper team for the mission. The Raven’s defended the Aircraft while on the ground in austere locations where no defense was in existence. The Vipers managed the electronics and communications end of things. They made sure the DV’s had communication with the outside world.</p>
      <p>We made friends with the Viper team and we squeezed the wifi password out of them with little effort. This may have been outside of their protocol, but when you are flying around in the countries we were the rules were more like guidelines. We were in the Wild Wild East, after all.</p>
      <p>As I was taking a break and sitting in a seat just behind the captains chair, I was browsing my normal blogs to find inspiration on this new adventure I was wanting to take on. What that was, I had no idea. I stumbled across a video of an inspiring man in Omaha, Nebraska. His name is Chris and he started Artifact Bag Company, an incredible brand making high quality bags and aprons. I immediately fell in love with the idea of crafting a piece that would last a lifetime.</p>
      <p><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0211/0380/t/4/assets/cockpit-c17.jpg"></p>
      <p>We finished out the mission after a few days and while I was back in Germany I did some research to find a sewing machine. I was fortunate enough to find an industrial machine that was being auctioned off at Fort Lewis Army Post, just next door to McChord Air Force Base, where I was from. I started a bidding war with some people, but was relentless to outbid anyone that would get in the way of me and my new dream. The machine was being sold “As Is”, so it’s working state was unknown.</p>
      <p>The auction expired while I was in flight home, so with zero control over the final moment of the auction it was left up to fate. When I landed in Washington I went through the debrief and packed all of my equipment into my car. I sat in my front seat and got my phone out to check the auction.</p>
      <p>I had won.</p>
      <p>With a sigh of relief I headed over to the Army Base and picked up my new machine. I had never sewn before, let alone worked with leather or canvas. I drove the machine to my friends retail shop that had a large back room he used for storage. We unloaded it and plugged it in.</p>
      <p>It worked.</p>
      <p>The rest, they say, is history.</p>
